<Layout title="Neurological Assessment Tools" description="Neurological assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Neurological</div>
  <h1>Neurological Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Scales and tools for assessing consciousness, neurological function, stroke, withdrawal, and cognitive status.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>GCS (Glasgow Coma Scale)</strong> — Assesses level of consciousness via Eye (1–4), Verbal (1–5), and Motor (1–6) responses. Total 3–15; ≤8 indicates severe impairment (intubation threshold).</li>
      <li><strong>FOUR Score (Full Outline of UnResponsiveness)</strong> — Alternative to GCS for intubated patients. Scores eye, motor, brainstem, and respiration components (0–4 each); captures brainstem reflexes GCS cannot.</li>
      <li><strong>Pediatric Coma Scale</strong> — Modified GCS adapted for infants and young children with age-appropriate verbal and motor response criteria.</li>
      <li><strong>NIH Stroke Scale (NIHSS)</strong> — 15-item stroke severity scale. Assesses consciousness, gaze, visual fields, facial palsy, motor, ataxia, sensory, language, dysarthria, and neglect. Score 0–42; higher = more severe.</li>
      <li><strong>CIWA-Ar (Clinical Institute Withdrawal Assessment for Alcohol)</strong> — 10-item scale for alcohol withdrawal severity. Scores nausea, tremor, sweating, anxiety, agitation, perceptual disturbances, headache, and orientation. Score ≥10 warrants pharmacologic treatment.</li>
      <li><strong>COWS (Clinical Opiate Withdrawal Scale)</strong> — 11-item observational scale for opioid withdrawal severity. Includes pulse, sweating, restlessness, pupil size, bone/joint aches, GI symptoms, tremor, yawning, anxiety, and piloerection.</li>
      <li><strong>CAM (Confusion Assessment Method)</strong> — Delirium screening algorithm with four features: acute onset/fluctuating course, inattention, disorganized thinking, and altered level of consciousness.</li>
      <li><strong>ABCD² Score</strong> — Predicts short-term stroke risk after TIA. Scores Age, Blood pressure, Clinical features, Duration of TIA, and Diabetes (0–7). Score ≥4 indicates high 2-day stroke risk.</li>
      <li><strong>CPSS (Cincinnati Prehospital Stroke Scale)</strong> — Three-item prehospital stroke screening: facial droop, arm drift, and abnormal speech. One abnormal finding = 72% stroke probability.</li>
      <li><strong>BE-FAST</strong> — Stroke recognition mnemonic: Balance loss, Eye disturbance, Face drooping, Arm weakness, Speech difficulty, Time to call 911.</li>
      <li><strong>Hunt and Hess Scale</strong> — Five-grade clinical classification of subarachnoid hemorrhage severity based on headache, meningismus, neurological deficits, and level of consciousness.</li>
      <li><strong>Fisher Scale</strong> — Radiologic grading of SAH on CT; grades 1–4 predict risk of vasospasm based on amount and distribution of subarachnoid blood.</li>
      <li><strong>Modified Rankin Scale (mRS)</strong> — Functional disability post-stroke graded 0–6. Score 0 = no symptoms; 6 = death. Primary outcome measure in stroke trials.</li>
      <li><strong>DRS (Disability Rating Scale)</strong> — Tracks TBI recovery from coma to community. Scores arousability, awareness, cognitive ability, dependence on others, and employability.</li>
      <li><strong>Rancho Los Amigos Scale</strong> — Eight-level cognitive recovery scale after brain injury ranging from Level I (no response) to Level VIII (purposeful, appropriate behavior).</li>
      <li><strong>JFK Coma Recovery Scale-Revised (CRS-R)</strong> — Standardized tool for minimally conscious state and vegetative state assessment. Evaluates auditory, visual, motor, oromotor, communication, and arousal functions.</li>
      <li><strong>Wessex Head Injury Matrix (WHIM)</strong> — 62-item hierarchical scale tracking emergence from coma and early rehabilitation progress after severe TBI.</li>
      <li><strong>Spinal Cord Independence Measure (SCIM)</strong> — Functional independence measure specific to spinal cord injury patients; assesses self-care, respiration/sphincter management, and mobility.</li>
      <li><strong>ASIA Impairment Scale</strong> — American Spinal Injury Association classification (A–E) for motor and sensory deficits after spinal cord injury.</li>
      <li><strong>UPDRS (Unified Parkinson's Disease Rating Scale)</strong> — Multidimensional Parkinson's disease rating across mentation/behavior, activities of daily living, motor examination, and complications of therapy.</li>
      <li><strong>EDSS (Expanded Disability Status Scale)</strong> — Rates disability in multiple sclerosis on a 0–10 scale based on functional system examinations; widely used in MS clinical trials.</li>
      <li><strong>FAB (Frontal Assessment Battery)</strong> — Six-item bedside tool assessing frontal lobe function: conceptualization, mental flexibility, motor programming, sensitivity to interference, inhibitory control, and environmental autonomy.</li>
      <li><strong>Trail Making Test</strong> — Two-part neuropsychological test; Part A assesses processing speed and attention; Part B assesses executive function and cognitive flexibility.</li>
      <li><strong>PSQI (Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index)</strong> — 19-item self-report questionnaire evaluating sleep quality and disturbances over the past month. Score &gt;5 indicates poor sleep quality.</li>
      <li><strong>Epworth Sleepiness Scale</strong> — Eight-item questionnaire rating likelihood of dozing in common situations. Score ≥10 indicates abnormal daytime sleepiness.</li>
      <li><strong>HIT-6 (Headache Impact Test)</strong> — Six-item questionnaire measuring the impact of headaches on daily functioning. Score ≥60 indicates severe impact.</li>
      <li><strong>MIDAS (Migraine Disability Assessment)</strong> — Five-item questionnaire measuring days of missed or reduced activity due to migraine over the past 3 months.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
